Sultan School District Families:

Today is National School Lunch Hero Day! Please join us in celebrating our Sultan School District Lunch Heros: Nita Lea, Lori Auckland, Audrey Bradley, Laura Howard, Celina Jacinto Flores, Kristi Kirkpatrick, Marsha Lauck, Yeimi Milian, Tammie Nollette, Lisa Parker, Jennifer Sherrill, Lalanya Steele, and Lynn Zimmerman.

Between preparing healthy food, adhering to strict nutrition standards, navigating student food allergies, and offering service with a smile, Sultan School District nutrition professionals have a lot on their plate. Please help us extend our thanks today, and everyday, to our School Lunch Heros for providing healthy meals each day to our students and families!

Want to learn more about the inspiration behind School Lunch Hero Day? Watching the video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?list=PLg9gpgNtuVmFuMPTW6zNjctgVXrzAEe2N&v=Hoj2g-4DEe0&feature=emb_logo

Sultan School District Families:

Join us Monday, April 13, 2020 in your yards and driveways as the Sultan School District Teacher/Staff Parade makes its way through your neighborhood to say HELLO!

(We have missed you so much and we wish we could give you hugs, but it‚Äôs so important you stay in your yard or on your driveway to keep everyone safe! If you are coming from a different neighborhood, please either watch from your car or keep with social distancing and stand at least 6 feet away from other families.)

Parade will start from Sultan Elementary School at 12:40 pm and from Gold Bar Elementary at 12:45 pm.

Anyone with symptoms should stay inside their home. Do not approach us. Stay away from the street. We will not be stopping. Decorate your window/yard/sidewalk/driveway so we know where to honk and wave!

We can‚Äôt wait to see you!

Sharing from and for Sultan High School and Sultan Middle Schools.

We are sad to announce that we are cancelling the CHOSEN event that was scheduled for this Saturday, March 14th. Snohomish Health District has recommended that school districts remain open at this time, but non-essential large gatherings be cancelled or rescheduled to minimize the spread of the Coronavirus, also called COVID-19. Sultan school District is following their recommendations by canceling the CHOSEN event. We apologize for any inconvenience this will cause. We are hoping to reschedule this event in the future.

For more information about the Snohomish Health District recommendation: http://www.snohd.org/blog.aspx

Dear Sultan Elementary Families,

As many of you already know, Sultan Elementary lost a beautiful, intelligent little girl to a tragic house fire on January 13th. This loss is hard for us to imagine and comprehend. The staff and community here at SES is grieving this loss and working with students and families to better understand and process the feelings and emotions associated with such losses.

Please consider giving, supporting, and helping this family to know that they are loved by all of us at Sultan Elementary and beyond. Please use this link https://www.gofundme.com/f/rebuild-life-and-home-after-fire to access the local Go Fund Me account.

A letter is being sent home to all Sultan Elementary families with more information. üêæ

Thank you,
Mr. Van Orden
Principal, Sultan Elementary

Canvas is a Learning Management System to support staff and students. It can be used as a learning resource for class materials or even to submit assignments electronically. Canvas is a great resource that neighboring districts and local colleges use as well! While not all staff will be using Canvas this Fall, your student may begin seeing it in a few classes. This is a new tool for us all and we appreciate your patience as our staff and students learn more about how to use it effectively!

Students login with their district email address and can access Canvas easily by going to www.sultanstudents.org and clicking the Canvas icon. Families will begin having access to Canvas next Spring- stay tuned!

Want to learn more? Visit our Canvas table at the upcoming Education Jamboree on October 14th.

Sultan School District Parents, Students, and Community Members:

Congratulations to our SHS wrestling team! The Turks finished in 11th place overall, second among Region 1 teams behind 10th place Mt. Baker. The Turks had 4 wrestlers medal, including 2nd place finishes by Aidan Fleming and Tyler Deason, a 3rd place finish by Luke Weaver, and an 8th place finish by Kameron Weaver. Skyler Talik and Donald Dennis didn‚Äôt medal, but did win two matches on Friday to advance to Saturday‚Äôs competition. CJ Vas also recorded a win at State on Friday. Hunter Jones and Cooper Johnsen competed hard but fell short of individual victories. Kiana Kendall also opened up the Championship Round Saturday night with another outstanding performance of the National Anthem. This year‚Äôs State tournament was an incredible challenge due to the lack of practices and two week break from competition from the weather. Our wrestlers did a great job taking on the extra challenges and competed hard and with class. Way to go Turks!

post_text:
SHS Principal Selection - Stakeholder Survey

The Sultan School District is involved in the search process for the next principal of Sultan High School. In August, 2018, the district hired Sarita Whitmire-Skeith as Interim Principal of Sultan High School. The decision was made at that time to re-post the position this spring to attract the best candidates possible.

We would like input from students, staff, parents/guardians, and community members on the characteristics desired in the next leader of Sultan High School. Please help us by completing the ‚ÄúSultan High School Principal Selection Survey‚Äù.

Your responses are anonymous. Survey results will be used by administration when screening, interviewing and ultimately when choosing the next principal of Sultan High School. Interviews are tentatively scheduled for the week of February 25, 2019. The survey will close on Friday, February 15, 2019. We appreciate your time to complete the survey and your involvement in Sultan High School.

Click here to take the Survey http://bit.ly/shssurvey2019

post_text:
Sultan School District Parents, Students, and Community Members:

New Assistant Principal at Sultan High School!

Sultan School District facilitated an in-depth interview process for four potential Sultan High School Assistant Principal candidates last night. The candidates participated in an intensive interview and a teaching and learning activity. These exchanges provided us with extensive information to make a clear decision.

We would like to re-introduce Ryan Malone to you as our new Assistant Principal at Sultan High School! Ryan taught English at Sultan High School for four years before getting his administrative credentials and taking an administrative position with Spring Academy. We are excited to welcome Ryan back to SHS and our Administrative team. He looks forward to meeting our SHS Turks, Parents, and Community Members in the upcoming weeks.

Welcome back Ryan!

Sultan School District Parents, Students, and Community Members:

Update from our Sultan School District Future Farmers of America (FFA) students Sierra, Robbie, Riley, and Savannah:

Robbie, Riley, Savannah, and I (Sierra) will be participating in the Evergreen Youth Livestock show at the Evergreen State Fair from August 23rd-August 26th. If anyone is interested in supporting us through donations/sponsorships or by buying our pigs, they can call 480-384-0584 or email stpierresierra@gmail.com.

Robbie is going to be a junior at SHS, Riley is going to be a freshman at SHS, Savannah is going to be in 6th grade at SMS, and I'm (Sierra) going to be a senior at SHS.

Pictures provided by Sierra St. Pierre-Perales:

Photo 1 - Sierra working with Oreo.
Photo 2 - Riley working with Buddy.
Photo 3 - Savannah working with Trouble.

Sultan School District Parents and Community Members:

Exciting Employment Opportunity for a ‚ÄúTrades Professional‚Äù with the Sultan School District:

If you have three or more years of full-time experience in welding and woodworking, and would enjoy teaching high school students, Sultan School District has a unique opportunity available. With 6,000 hours (3 years) experience you can become conditionally certificated with the State of Washington to teach Vocational Classes at Sultan High School. Other classes you might teach include Horticulture, Agriculture Mechanics and Aquaculture. You would need to become certificated by September 1, 2018. This is a full-time teaching position beginning in September.

Check out the job posting on our website at https://www.sultanschools.org/human-recources

Parents/Community Members! Do you recognize this person? They broke into a classroom last night (May 9th) at 9:15pm and left at 9:30pm. Items taken were a LOT of candy and a staff, grey laptop. This person knew exactly what they were doing, came straight on campus with a chair, to the window, went in, then out the door, grabbed chair and walked west off campus. If you recognize, please call sultan elementary (360-793-9830) and leave your information with Mr. Van Orden. The Snohomish County Sheriff has also been contacted and is working with the school. Thank you!

Sultan School District Parents, Students, and Community Members:

Please join us in congratulating our Sultan Middle School students on their repeated Washington State Science and Engineering Fair achievements! Way to go Skyhawks!
shared_text:
Sultan Middle School
March 26, 2018 at 8:54 PM ¬∑

Congratulations goes out to the Skyhawk Science Fair Team for their efforts this weekend at the 61st annual Washington State Science and Engineering Fair in Bremerton!

The 6th grade Skyhawks repeated as State Champions in the Jr. Division on Friday, while the 7th grade team grabbed the top spot in the Middle school division bringing home another state championship trophy on Saturday.

In addition to team victories, 7 students have qualified to compete in the prestigious Broadcom Communications science competition in Washington DC later this year. This competition is reserved for the top 10% of the top young scientists in the nation. Each student attending the final competition will receive an all expenses paid trip to Washington DC for themselves and a chaperone, 500 dollars in spending money, and the opportunity to be paid from 1000 to 25000 for their ideas.

Individual results will be posted on the school Facebook page when verified by the State Science Director.

Sultan School District Parents, Students, and Community Members:
We would like to thank Walmart Vision Center in Monroe for sending two managers to help with our student vision screening this year! They spent three full days at our schools: one day at Sultan Middle School, one day at Gold Bar Elementary, and a third day at Sultan Elementary.

This year Washington State schools are mandated to test near (reading) vision as well as distance vision for all kindergartners, 1st, 2nd, 3rd, 5th and 7th graders. The nurses also test hearing for these grades.

Having Walmart donate so much of their time and energy was a huge help to the Sultan School District and the school nurses!

Deborah Shirley, RN
Carol Sweeten, RN

post_text:
Update for Parents, Students, and Community Members:

All of our schools are now in session and progressing as usual. We have law enforcement presence within the district. The investigation into the anonymous post between two individuals is being handled by law enforcement officials. The late start decision was made after looking at the limited facts that we have and consulting with law enforcement officials to allow time for law enforcement clearance and presence within the district. Part of the issue with anonymous posting forums/apps/websites is that they are very difficult for law enforcement to trace and track down the validity of what was posted and who posted them. Thank you to those individuals who notified law enforcement and school district officials about the post. These are very challenging situations to deal with when we have such limited information. Student safety is, and will always be, our first priority.

Sincerely,
Dan Chaplik, Superintendent

Hello,

The Sultan School District and Sultan Education Foundation would like to invite you to our 2017 Education Jamboree! This event will be held on 9/26/2017 from 5:30-7:30pm at Sultan High School, 13715 310th Ave SE, Sultan.

Our goal is to show you all of the exciting educational opportunities at each of our schools and supporting departments, as well as offer you a tour of Sultan High School. This event will also provide you an opportunity to get involved with programs or organizations that you have an interest in as well as welcome your input in planning for our future as a school district.

The Sultan Education Foundation is graciously providing hot dogs and the SMS PTO and Sodexo, our food service provider, will be supplying the rest. We will also provide transportation to this event from Gold Bar Elementary School starting at 5:10pm with buses running every 20 minutes for pickups and drop-offs to and from the Jamboree.

We look forward to connecting with you at this event!

Parents please read the following message from SHS:

Today, Thursday, May 25, 2017....Multiple students reported during lunch today that a student said yesterday that he intended to blow up the school.

We went into a lock down at Sultan High School to investigate. For our students and staffs safety our building was surrounded by deputies and a plan was put in place for a full evacuation which would have taken us to the stadium for attendance and out 8th street to Mountain View Church.

It turned out to be words only. The student has been expelled with legal action pending.

Dear Sultan School District Families, Staff, and Community Members:

Our Board of Directors would like to collect information about your interest in possibly changing the school colors at Gold Bar Elementary School, Sultan Elementary School, Sultan Middle School, Sky Valley Options, and the Sultan School District to match the colors at Sultan High School. The survey will be open from 3/7/2017 through the end of the day on 3/20/2017. Once the survey is closed, the survey responses will be shared with our Board of Directors.

Thank you for your time and effort in responding to our survey!

post_text: This message is for all Sultan High School parents. You will not be able to enter the SHS campus from the main entrance to pick up your student today. A live wire fell across the main entrance and the entrance is blocked with emergency personnel who are fixing the wire. There is no electricity at the high school currently because of the problem. All students are safe but we need your cooperation in picking up your student today. Please wait until all busses leave before attempting to pick up your student. You must enter on 8th street. Again, please wait until all busses have picked up students and left the campus before picking up your student. Girls basketball practice has been cancelled today as well as other after school activities. Wrestling and the boys basketball games will be held as scheduled - power should be restored by then.

post_text:
January is School Board Recognition Month!

School board members are stewards of the district resources and vision. They set standards for achievement and diligently evaluate to ensure those standards are met. They decide how to distribute limited resources, sometimes making very difficult decisions. They connect and problem solve. Board members question, examine, revise and revisit issues to ensure continuous improvement.

Please take a moment to express your appreciation to Russ Sumpter, Patty Fountain, Tracy Cotterill, Ed Husmann and Cindy Buoy as well as student representative Sierra Huff when you see them out and about in our community.

We appreciate our School Board, and because of their selfless efforts, we thank them.

We will continue to work diligently to ensure student safety throughout our community. The incident is being investigated.
